# Conventional Commits (release-please)

Every commit on `main` must follow [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/). `release-please` parses commit messages to decide version bumps, changelog entries, and when to open a release PR. Non-conventional messages (including default merge titles) are **silently ignored**.

## Format

```text
<type>[optional scope][optional !]: <description>

[optional body]

[optional footer(s)]
```

- **type** — lowercase, required (`feat`, `fix`, `docs`, `chore`, …)
- **scope** — optional, in parentheses: `feat(serve): …`
- **description** — imperative mood, lowercase start, no trailing period
- **!** after type/scope — breaking change (also add `BREAKING CHANGE:` footer when needed)

## Types and version impact (pre-1.0)

| Type | Bump | Changelog |
|------|------|-----------|
| `feat:` | minor | Features |
| `fix:`, `perf:` | patch | Bug Fixes / Performance |
| `docs:` | none | Documentation |
| `feat!:` / `fix!:` / `BREAKING CHANGE:` | minor (major post-1.0) | highlighted |
| `chore:`, `refactor:`, `test:`, `ci:`, `style:` | none | hidden |

## Examples

```text
feat(update): add --scaffold-only flag to loco update
fix(tests): compare manifest version to pyproject.toml
chore: rename PyPI distribution to loco-llm-cli
docs: document branch protection for CI checks
```

## Avoid

```text
Rename PyPI distribution to loco-llm-cli          # no type — ignored
Merge pull request #4 from mtopcu1/bugfix/...     # merge commit — ignored
Fixed the tests.                                  # free-form — ignored
```

When creating commits or suggesting commit messages, always use conventional format. For PRs merged with squash, the **squash commit title** must be conventional too.
